Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a full #kettle{}.

Put the @soy sauce{15%ml} into a #medium bowl{}.

Add the @British chicken thighs{4} to the bowl and coat evenly.

> Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Lay the chicken thighs on a large #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{} and spoon over any remaining soy from the bowl.

Sprinkle the @roasted white sesame seeds{5%g} over the chicken.

When the oven is hot, roast on the middle shelf until browned and cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, pour the boiling water from the kettle into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{0.25%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @jasmine rice{150%g} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{} and leave to the side until ready to serve.

While the rice cooks, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @pak choi{1}, then thinly slice widthways.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @sliced mushrooms{80%g} and fry for ~{2%minutes}.

Add the @coleslaw mix{120%g} and pak choi to the mushrooms, with a drizzle more @oil{} if needed.

Stir-fry until the veg has softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @bulgogi sauce{150%g}, then bring to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}.

Remove from the heat.

Once the chicken is cooked, slice thinly and add to the pan with the veg, along with any soy glaze from the tray. Toss to combine.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and spoon into your #bowls{}.

Top with the bulgogi veg and sesame soy baked chicken. Enjoy!